# Get upper triangle of the correlation matrix
  get_upper_tri <- function(cormat){ 
    cormat[lower.tri(cormat)]<- NA
    return(cormat)
  }

# Rename the correlation coefficient value
upper_tri <- get_upper_tri(cormat)

# Use correlation between variables as distance
reorder_cormat <- function(cormat){ 
dd <- as.dist((1-cormat)/2)
hc <- hclust(dd)
cormat <-cormat[hc$order, hc$order]
}

# Reorder the correlation matrix
cormat <- reorder_cormat(cormat)
upper_tri <- get_upper_tri(cormat)

# Melt the correlation matrix
melted_cormat <- melt(upper_tri, na.rm = TRUE)

For the classical LS model, we will review the four explanatory variables. In the output above, it is evident that ‘paved’ is not significant as the p-value exceeds α = 0.05. There is not enough evidence and therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis (H0: β0 = 0). If we proceed with the other three variables, we can assume that ‘tax’, ‘income’, and ‘license’ explains most of ‘consumption’ (response variable, y).

As we discussed in the lecture, we need to also calculate the degrees of freedom. For this exercise, we have 48 observations minus the four exploratory variables. The intercept needs to be accounted for as well, which equates to 1. To get 43 degrees of freedom, the equation would be the following: 48 - 4 - 1 = 43.

F-stat is significant, and therefore, we reject the null hypothesis since α = 0.05. A model is qualitatively good if the Fisher test is signifigant an R-squared big.
- (H0: β1 = β2 = β3 = β4)

Just as before in the classical LS model, we need to calculate the degrees of freedom. For this exercise, we have 48 observations minus the four exploratory variables. Residual Analysis

par(mfrow = c(2,2)) # Organizes graphs in a specific order
plot(Conso.ls, col = "blue") # Plots the linear regression

par(mfrow = c(1,4)) # Organizes graphs in a specific order
PlotResidX(Conso[, 1:2], Conso.ls$residuals, col= "blue") # Creates the residuals plots and utilized color

PlotResidX(Conso[, 3:4], Conso.ls$residuals, col= "blue")

# Function to graph autocorrelations
acf(resid(Conso.ls), main="Residuals Autocorrelation: LS")

Residuals vs Fitted
With any model, the residuals should assume the following:
1. ± as many negatives as positives (values), distributed around zero
2. No structure
3. No extreme values
To ensure this criteria is met, we use the Residuals vs Fitted to check the lack of structure or presence of extreme values. It is important to note the following:
- A residual will be considered large if its absolute value exceeds (approximately) 2σ(hat)
- When n is large, a residual will be considered large if its absolute value exceeds (approximately) 4σ(hat) (otherwise, too many residues will be considered large!)

All values are weighted evenly in an LS model, including potential outliers. As mentioned above, we need to ensure that the residuals are within our limits. Referring back to the summary(Conso.ls) output, the model’s residual standard error is 66.31. If we multiple by ±2, we return our estimate. In this case, let us focus on the upper limit of 132.62. Visually, we can determine that the point ‘40’, falls outside that of 132.62 and would be considered large. Even though there one extreme, the residuals seem to follow the other two criteria above. Additionally, I would like to point out that the constant variance assumption is assumed to be violated since that the residuals have a wide range.

Normal Q-Q
To check the normality of the errors εi we do a normal Q-Q plot of the residuals. For this graph, we can use the “thickness of a pencil approach.” If we were to put the pencil on the regression line, it is immediately noticed that the data point ‘40’ is not underneath. If we did not consider that extreme value, the Q-Q plot seems to be normally distributed minus the small departure at the tail part.

Scale-Location
As seen in the other graphs, there is an extreme residual. We know that this is considered extreme because of the following: 2xσ.

Residuals vs Leverage
The (40) outlier has a big influence as it is underneath the 1 line to the right that refers to Cook’s distance.

Autocorrelation
The ACF plot shows that there is no evidence of autocorrelation between the residuals.

From the information gathered above, we can conclude that we would not use the LS model due to it did not meeting the criteria of no extreme values.

Unlike the classic LS model, we will say our conclusion first. Based off of the assumptions below, we will validate our M-estimation at 90% efficiency model. Here is why:

Residuals vs Fitted
With any model, the residuals should assume the following:
1. ± as many negatives as positives (values), distributed around zero
2. No structure
3. No extreme values
To ensure this criteria is met, we use the Residuals vs Fitted to check the lack of structure or presence of extreme values. It is important to note the following:
- A residual will be considered large if its absolute value exceeds (approximately) 2σ(hat)
- When n is large, a residual will be considered large if its absolute value exceeds (approximately) 4σ(hat) (otherwise, too many residues will be considered large!)

In robust model, outliers are weighted differently. Regardless, we still need to ensure that the residuals are within our limits. Referring back to the summary(Conso.m90) output, the model’s residual standard error is 45.52. If we multiple that value by ±2, we return our estimate. In this case, let us focus on the upper limit of 91.04. Visually, we can determine that the point ‘40’ along with ‘19’, and ‘45’, fall outside that of 91.04 and would be considered large. With the M-estimation model though, these values are minimized. Even though there are three extremes, the residuals seem to follow the other two criteria above.

Normal Q-Q
To check the normality of the errors εi we do a normal Q-Q plot of the residuals. For this graph, we can approach the M-estimator model as we did with LS. In this Q-Q plot, there is a slight difference with the graph outcome. This time, we notice that there are three values that seem to depart by the tail. Otherwise, Q-Q plot seems to be normally distributed.

Scale-Location
As seen in the other graphs, there is an extreme residual. We know that this is considered extreme because of the following: 2xσ.

Residuals vs Leverage
The (40) outlier has a big influence as it is underneath the 1 line to the right that refers to Cook’s distance.

Autocorrelation
The ACF plot shows that there is no evidence of autocorrelation between the residuals as it does not exceed the confidence interval.

As stated above, we assume that criteria are met due to the following:
- Normal distribution (QQ plot)
- The robust adjusted R-squared improved to 0.75381 compared to LS’ 0.6488
- No sign of autocorrelation

Conclusion

We need to consider which model is a better overall fit: LS or M-estimation. The following reasons indicate why one an analyst would choose one over the other:

Ordinary Least Squares Estimation (LS)

Advantages: efficient and unbiased estimators (in a finite sample)
Disadvantage: model is very sensitive to deviations (i.e. extreme values) from hypothesis

M-estimator at 90% efficiency

From our LS analysis, we are aware of the extreme value at ‘40’. Therefore, choosing LS would not be the best method. Unlike the LS model, the resulting M-estimator is convergent, robust and the loss of efficiency is less as it can be controlled. Plus, we know that the adjusted R-squared is higher. We need to watch out for the degree of efficiency because as c decreases, the M-estimator will be more resistant to extreme values. To exemplify this, I demonstrate below how the models differ and to show how we could make a model (60% efficiency) less efficient.

The graph below represents each explanatory variable’s various regression lines and how the models handle extreme values.

Model 1 = LS Estimator

Model 2 = M-estimator at 90%

Model 3 = M-estimator at 60%

# Creates various linear regression models and compares graphically

par(mfrow=c(2,2))

plot(Conso$tax,Conso$consumption, main="Tax vs. Consumption Regression Lines", xlab = "Consumption", ylab = "Tax")
abline(lm(Conso$consumption ~ Conso$tax), col="blue")
abline (lmRob(consumption ~ tax , data=Conso), col="red")
abline (lmRob(consumption ~ tax , data=Conso,control=lmRob.control(efficiency=0.60)), col="orange")

plot(Conso$income,Conso$consumption, main="Income vs. Consumption Regression Lines", xlab = "Consumption", ylab = "Income")
abline(lm(Conso$consumption ~ Conso$income), col="blue")
abline (lmRob(consumption ~ income , data=Conso), col="red")
abline (lmRob(consumption ~ income , data=Conso,control=lmRob.control(efficiency=0.60)), col="orange")

plot(Conso$paved,Conso$consumption, main="Paved vs. Consumption Regression Lines", xlab = "Consumption", ylab = "Paved")
abline(lm(Conso$consumption ~ Conso$paved), col="blue")
abline (lmRob(consumption ~ paved , data=Conso), col="red")
abline (lmRob(consumption ~ paved , data=Conso,control=lmRob.control(efficiency=0.60)), col="orange")

plot(Conso$license,Conso$consumption, main="License vs. Consumption Regression Lines", xlab = "Consumption", ylab = "License")
abline(lm(Conso$consumption ~ Conso$license), col="blue")
abline (lmRob(consumption ~ license , data=Conso), col="red")
abline (lmRob(consumption ~ license , data=Conso,control=lmRob.control(efficiency=0.60)), col="orange")

If we review each graph, one will notice that the extreme values are primarily above zero. The LS model takes this into account and is “pulled up” due to those data points. The M-estimation at 90% though, the outliers are minimized because of how the model is structured. As we decrease efficiency to 60%, the extreme values are not taken into account as much since c has decreased. This can be accounted for by the slope of the orange line.

1. What are the estimated values for the βjs using classic (LS) and robust (M-estimation) estimation?

Value LS M at 90%
β0 - intercept 377.3 456.730208
β1 - tax -34.79 -15.937399
β2 - income -0.06659 -0.076470
β3 - paved -0.002426 -0.001821
β4 - license 1336 946.474273

2. How do you interpret them?

OLS model
consumption = β0 + β1(tax) + β2(income) + β3(paved) + β4(license)
consumption = 377.3 - 34.79(tax) - 0.06659(income) - 0.002426(paved) + 1336(license)

M-Estimation model at 90%
Consumption = β0 + β1(tax) + β2(income) + β3(paved) + β4(license)
Consumption = 456.730208 - 15.937399(tax) - 0.076470(income) + 0.001821(paved) + 946.474273(license)

Interpretation
- Intercept (β0): The intercept contains the response variable (y). If the explanatory variables are equal to zero, the consumption of the country is equal to
(LS): 377.3 million of gallons and
(M-estimation): 456.730208 million of gallons

  • Tax (β1): On average, if there is an increase of $0.01 in taxes on the gasoline price, gas consumption will decrease by
    (LS): 34.79 million of gallons and
    (M-estimation): 15.937399 million of gallons

  • Income(β2): On average, if there is an increase of $1.00 in income per year, gas consumption will decrease by
    (LS): 0.06659 million of gallons and
    (M-estimation): 0.076470 million of gallons

  • Paved (β3): On average, if there is an increase of 1 mile, gas consumption will increase by
    (LS): 0.002426 million of gallons and
    (M-estimation): 0.001821 million of gallons

  • License (β4): On average, if there is an increase of 1 in the proportion of the population having a driver’s licence, gas consumption will increase by
    (LS): 1336 million of gallons and
    (M-estimation): 946.474273 million of gallons

3. Are the parameters significant?
There is a commonality between the LS and M-estimation models. They both have explanatory variables that are not significant in terms of α = 0.05. This automatically means that since their p-values are higher than alpha. Therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. In both models, ‘paved’ is not significant and in the M-estimation, neither is ‘tax’. Keeping the M-estimation model in mind, we can consider that ‘income’ and ‘license’ explain most of consumption. If we decided to remove the variables ‘paved’ and ‘tax’, we could then recreate the model and test how it performs. For now, we will leave that for the next analysis!

4 How large are the R2s for your models (classic and robust)? How do you interpret them?
R-squared is the degree to which input variables (predictor variables) explain the variation of output variables (predicted variables). The adjusted value adjusts for predictors that are not significant in a regression model between 0 and 1. In this case, the adjusted R-squared for the classical LS model is 0.6488 and the robust model’s is at 0.75381. The R-squared shows how the regression line fits to the data. The closer to 1 the better goodness-of-fit. In this situation, the M-estimation at 90% has the higher value.

5. How do you interpret the ‘Test of Bias’ results?
For both models, their p-values which are referenced in the ‘Test for Bias’ table show that each are higher than α = 0.05. We fail to reject the null hypothesis and there is no bias.

  get_upper_tri <- function(cormat){ 
    cormat[lower.tri(cormat)]<- NA
    return(cormat)

# Use correlation between variables as distance
reorder_cormat <- function(cormat){ 
dd <- as.dist((1-cormat)/2)

When we have multicollinearity, there are several issues that arise:
- The coefficient of determination R-squared is underestimated. The regressors explain the same part of the variance of the response
- Increase in the variance of the estimators of the β coefficients. The parameters have more chances of not be significant because the corresponding variables share between them the same part of explication of the response
- The inversion of XTX becomes impossible

We still can observe that ‘goudron’ and ‘CO’ have a positively linear relationship (correlation at 95.7%), and that are no other patterns in the data.

For the classical LS model, we will review the two explanatory variables. In the output above, the intercept and ‘poids’ are not significant as their p-values exceed α = 0.05. There is not enough evidence and therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis (H0: β0 = 0). Since we know that the intercept and ‘poids’ does not explain the response variable, the conclusion would be that ‘goudron’ has an effect on ‘CO’.

As we discussed in the lecture, we need to also calculate the degrees of freedom. For this exercise, we have 25 observations minus the two exploratory variables. The intercept needs to be accounted for as well, which equates to 1. To get 22 degrees of freedom, the equation would be the following: 25 - 2 - 1 = 22.

Since the F-stat is significant, we reject the null hypothesis since α = 0.05. A model is qualitatively good if the Fisher test is signifigant an R-squared big.
- (H0: β1 = β2 = β3 = β4)

Residual Analysis

par(mfrow = c(2,2)) 
plot(Ciga2.ls) # Plots the classical linear model

par(mfrow = c(1,3))
PlotResidX(Ciga2[, 1:3], Ciga2.ls$residuals, col= "blue") # Sourcing from PlotResidx

# Use ACF() to create an autocorrelation, time series table
acf(resid(Ciga2.ls), main="Residuals Autocorrelation: LS")

Residuals vs Fitted
With any model, the residuals should assume the following:
1. ± as many negatives as positives (values), distributed around zero
2. No structure
3. No extreme values
To ensure this criteria is met, we use the Residuals vs Fitted to check the lack of structure or presence of extreme values. It is important to note the following:
- A residual will be considered large if its absolute value exceeds (approximately) 2σ(hat)
- When n is large, a residual will be considered large if its absolute value exceeds (approximately) 4σ(hat) (otherwise, too many residues will be considered large!)

All values are weighted evenly in an LS model, including potential outliers. As mentioned above, we need to ensure that the residuals are within our limits. Referring back to the summary(Ciga2.ls) output, the model’s residual standard error is 1.428. If we multiple that value by ±2, we return our estimate. In this case, let us focus on the lower limit of 2.856. Visually, we can determine that the point ‘3’, falls outside that of -2.856 and would be considered large. Even though there is one extreme, the residuals seem to follow the other two criteria above.

Normal Q-Q
To check the normality of the errors εi we do a normal Q-Q plot of the residuals. For this graph, we can use the “thickness of a pencil approach.” If we were to put the pencil on the regression line, it is immediately noticed that the data point ‘3’ is not underneath. If we did not consider that extreme value, the Q-Q plot seems to be normally distributed minus the departure at the tail part.

Scale-Location
As seen in the other graphs, there is an extreme residual. We know that this is considered extreme because of the following: 2xσ.

Residuals vs Leverage
The (3) outlier has a big influence as it is underneath the 1 line to the right that refers to Cook’s distance.

Autocorrelation
The ACF plot shows that there is evidence of autocorrelation between the residuals as lag 1, 2, and 4 exceed the two standard error cut-off value.

From the information gathered above, we can conclude that we would not use the LS model due to it did not meeting the criteria of no extreme values and have autocorrelations of the residuals.

Unlike the classic LS model, we will say our conclusion first. Based off of the assumptions below, we will validate our M-estimation at 90% efficiency model. Here is why:

Residuals vs Fitted
With any model, the residuals should assume the following:
1. ± as many negatives as positives (values), distributed around zero
2. No structure
3. No extreme values
To ensure this criteria is met, we use the Residuals vs Fitted to check the lack of structure or presence of extreme values. It is important to note the following:
- A residual will be considered large if its absolute value exceeds (approximately) 2σ(hat)
- When n is large, a residual will be considered large if its absolute value exceeds (approximately) 4σ(hat) (otherwise, too many residues will be considered large!)

In robust model, outliers are weighted differently. Regardless, we still need to ensure that the residuals are within our limits. Referring back to the summary(Ciga2.m90) output, the model’s residual standard error is 1.302. If we multiple that value by ±2, we return our estimate. In this case, let us focus on the lower limit of 2.3604 Visually, we can determine that the point ‘3’ fall outside that of two standard error threshold and would be considered large. With the M-estimation model though, these values are minimized. Even though there is an extreme, the residuals seem to follow the other two criteria above.

Normal Q-Q
To check the normality of the errors εi we do a normal Q-Q plot of the residuals. For this graph, we can approach the M-estimator model as we did with LS. In both situations, the extreme value is in the lower left hand corner where it departs from the tail. Otherwise, Q-Q plot seems to be normally distributed.

Scale-Location
As seen in the other graphs, there is an extreme residual. We know that this is considered extreme because of the following: 2xσ.

Residuals vs Leverage
The (3) outlier has a big influence as it is underneath the 1 line to the right that refers to Cook’s distance.

Autocorrelation
The ACF plot shows that there is no evidence of autocorrelation between the residuals as it does not exceed the confidence interval.

As stated above, we assume that criteria are met due to the following:
- Normal distribution (QQ plot)
- The robust adjusted R-squared improved to 0.937932 compared to LS’ 0.9093
- No sign of autocorrelation

Conclusion

We need to consider which model is a better overall fit: LS or M-estimation. The following reasons indicate why one an analyst would choose one over the other:

Ordinary Least Squares Estimation (LS)

Advantages: efficient and unbiased estimators (in a finite sample)
Disadvantage: model is very sensitive to deviations (i.e. extreme values) from hypothesis

M-estimator at 90% efficiency

From our LS analysis, we are aware of the extreme value at ‘3’. Therefore, choosing LS would not be the best method. Unlike the LS model, the resulting M-estimator is convergent, robust and the loss of efficiency is less as it can be controlled. Plus, we know that the adjusted R-squared is higher. We need to watch out for the degree of efficiency because as c decreases, the M-estimator will be more resistant to extreme values. To exemplify this, I demonstrated in Conso’s analysis how the models differ and to show how we could make a model (60% efficiency) less efficient.

1. What are the estimated values for the βjs using classic (LS) and robust (M-estimation) estimation?

Value LS M at 90%
β0 - intercept 3.11433 -0.4898
β1 - goudron 0.80419 0.9174
β2 - poids -0.42287 2.1056

2. How do you interpret them?

OLS model
CO = β0 + β1(goudron) + β2(poids) CO = 3.11433 + 0.80419(goudron) - 0.42287(poids)

M-Estimation model at 90%
CO = β0 + β1(goudron) + β2(poids) CO = -0.4898 + 0.9174(goudron) + 2.1056(poids)

Interpretation
- Intercept (β0): The intercept contains the response variable (y). If the explanatory variables are equal to zero, the CO emission of a cigarette is equal to
(LS): 3.11433 mg of CO and
(M-estimation): -0.4898 mg of CO

  • Goudron (β1): On average, if there is an increase of 1 mg of goudron into a cigarette will increase by
    (LS): 0.80419 mg of CO and
    (M-estimation): 15.937399 mg of CO

  • Poids (β2): On average, if there is an increase of 1 gr of a cigarette, CO emission will decrease by
    (LS): 0.42287 mg of CO and increase by
    (M-estimation): 2.1056 mg of CO

3. Are the parameters significant?
There is a commonality between the LS and M-estimation models. They both have ‘poids’ and the intercept that are not significant in terms of α = 0.05. This automatically means that since their p-values are higher than alpha. Therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Keeping the M-estimation model in mind, we can consider that ‘goudron’ can explain most of consumption.

4 How large are the R2s for your models (classic and robust)? How do you interpret them?
R-squared is the degree to which input variables (predictor variables) explain the variation of output variables (predicted variables). The adjusted value adjusts for predictors that are not significant in a regression model between 0 and 1. In this case, the adjusted R-squared for the classical LS model is 0.9093 and the robust model’s is at 0.937932. The R-squared shows how the regression line fits to the data. The closer to 1 the better goodness-of-fit. In this situation, the M-estimation at 90% has the higher value.

5. How do you interpret the ‘Test of Bias’ results?
For both models, their p-values which are referenced in the ‘Test for Bias’ table show that each are higher than α = 0.05. We fail to reject the null hypothesis and there is no bias.
